Some Capetonians are putting their vacation plans on hold due to rising COVID-19 infections. The Western Cape government has been discussing implementing localised restrictions in a bid to stifle a resurgence in some areas. The Garden Route has already stopped any planned public events in the region. eNCA's Monique Mortlock has the story. Courtesy #DStv403 DURBAN - At least one of South Africa's top holiday destination is cancelling major parties and events this festive season.
The KwaZulu-Natal government said hosting the events won't be allowed as COVID-19 infections are on the rise in the province. READ: Coronavirus in SA: Second wave or resurgence? It said its decision is informed by advice from medical and scientific experts. Premier Sihle Zikalala said the province is edging closer to a second wave of the virus. READ: COVID-19 in SA: Is another 'family meeting' looming? He said the provincial government understands the economic impact of not hosting major events, which inject million of rand into the province's purse but Zikalala said protecting the lives of the citizens is more important. The premier has urged people to visit his province, saying they can hold small activities. *Watch how other provinces are handling festive celebrations and the coronavirus pandemic above.